Reposting as requested.
>It’s a curious thing, the little changes one finds between differing societies, you muse as you lay in your bed and idly browse a news site on your phone.
>You’ve only been in this odd world of anthropomorphic animals for about a year, and what a wild year it’s been. Thankfully, the government of your new home nation was kind to you despite the alarming circumstances, so you found yourself with citizenship and assistance until you were on your feet. The territory is one controlled primarily by canines, like dogs, foxes, and wolves, and you’ve enjoyed a strange popularity because of it.
>Not because of being an ‘alien’, no, but specifically for being ‘human.’ When little-seen species visit the territory, they don’t get any special treatment. You, though?
>Foxes are often skittish near you, but warm up rather quickly. It’s not long before they abandon their caution and become chatterboxes.
>Wolves generally find you likable from the get-go, even if they seem oddly wary. Many wolves are insular and superstitious, but you seem to just slide right through their suspicion without tripping any alarms after just a few hours of being acquaintances.
>Dogs?
>Dogs LOVE you.
>To this day, you’ve yet to meet a dog who didn’t take a shine to you within minutes, if not instantly. Little was needed to cement a friendship with one, as they just seemed eager to be around you. It was… concerning, at first, but you’ve since gotten over it.
>Ha, boring old Anon is the most popular guy in town here. That’s a thought.
1/4

Quoted By: >>42885424 >>42885504 >>42887624
>>42885394
>But perhaps there’s a reason to it.
>You can only call the phenomenon that brought you here a ‘spasm’ in space. If you, a living being could cross totally intact, who’s to say there isn’t more bleed over? Is the attitude in you the resurgence of old instinct from a time before history where there was another or even several humans? Maybe that phenomenon wasn’t a space distortion, but a TIME distortion. For all you know, you’re millions of years in the future after humans went extinct, and evolution did its thing.
>Multiple sapient species co-existing at once is… implausible, but not impossible, you guess.
>You glance back at your phone. It’s a bog-standard smart-phone without any bells or whistles, but it carries the hallmarks of design for non-human use.
>The smooth glass-back that was favored so much back home is gone, as glass just slips too easily in large, furry hands. Instead, the back of your phone is covered in a thin layer of rubber for better grip.
>The call speaker is also oriented in a non-human way, pointed straight up on the chassis as to point towards ears on top of the head.
>On the sides, the volume rocker and the power button are enlarged. It looks silly in human hands, but in the comparatively clumsy paws of someone else, the buttons are just the right size to be used without difficulty.
>There is also the 3rd button, one that toggles light modes quickly and easily. With so many different types of eyes to cater to, the manufacturer made sure to account for color blindness and light sensitivity.
>Oh the terrible things xenobiologists back home would do to have one of these mass-produced devices.
>The sound of your apartment’s door opening and shutting makes you look away from the news article on your phone. You scoot to the side and make room on the bed, already knowing whos coming in.
>”Anon? Are you awake?”
2/4

Her face is a hodge-podge of white, brown, and black fur, with tired hazel eyes that light up as she lays them upon you. Although her shirt is tight and low-cut, anything untoward is hidden by the impressive tuft of fluffy fur on her chest and above her breasts. Behind her, her tail wags slowly.

Anonymous Wed 03 Nov 2021 22:34:45 No.42891178 Report
Quoted By: >>42891295 >>42891310 >>42892481
>>42890569
Not drawfren, but

The other anon mentioned /ic/ resources, though there are several better ones out there. For example, if you have seen the "Loomis head" method, its good for beginners because of tis simplicity. However, its not accurate to life almost at all. Heads are not spherical in shape, and have far too many plains for the Loomis method to capture accurately. Again though, its just a good base for beginners.

What I have done in order to practice is merely studying from great anatomically detailed drawings by Gottfried Bammes. I like his stuff a lot and they helped me with anatomy a ton. You can literally find his work in google images, just search up "Gottfried Bammes [SUBJECT, ex: Arms, Legs, etc]" I would recommend going through each part of the body individually until you have improved all around, then go back again from the top of your anatomy list and repeat.

You will then want to practice putting the figure together, piece by piece. You will want to study figure drawings as a primary focus first, then study the theory of gesture afterwords because gesture is less technical skill as it is mileage+theory coming together to form a new concept.

Overall, so long as you make good use of your materials, gestures and figures will come easier later once you start understanding how to simplify each form of the body and quickly put it onto the paper with confident lines.

Typically I practice whatever I feel needs the most improvement, and I don't stop until I'm satisfied with it. For example; I often times just lay down and practice drawing different faces and expressions, trying to make everything as fluid and cute as I possibly can. This process can take as long as 30 thirty minutes to an hour, but that's just me. I don't want to spend too long on something or too little, so I try and be as productive as possible. Another good thing to always practice and keep up on is anatomy. Sometimes it can be fun, too. Always keep in mind that no matter what you are practicing and how much progress you're making, having confidence in your abilities can and will help immensely. Having confidence in yourself can aid in the learning process, and greatly increase the effectiveness of your practice sessions. Some days it might be hard to notice any improvement, whilst other days it might be very noticeable. You've got to take it with stride and push through, no matter what. You might be surprised by what you can achieve with just some confidence and consistency. Also, I'm sorry I took so long to get back to you, I type awfully slow sometimes. I hope that this helps. If you ever want to go into more detail on the the specifics of my particular drawing process, or if you have any other questions, than you can message me anytime on https://drawfren.sofurry.com/ I believe in you, fren.

Man’s finitude, his dread of death and of the overwhelmingness of life.
The schizophrenic feels these more than anyone else because he has not been able to build the confident defenses that a person normally uses to deny them.
The schizophrenic’s misfortune is that he has been burdened with extra anxieties, extra guilt, extra helplessness, an even more unpredictable and unsupportive environment. He is not surely seated in his body, has no secure base from which to negotiate a defiance of and a denial of the real nature of the world.
The parents have made him massively inept as an organism. He has to contrive extra-ingenious and extra-desperate ways of living in the world that will keep him from being torn apart by experience, since he is already almost apart. We see again confirmed the point of view that a person’s character is a defense against despair, an attempt to avoid insanity because of the real nature of the world.
Searles looks at schizophrenia precisely as the result of the inability to shut out terror, as a desperate style of living with terror.
Frankly I don’t know anything more cogent that needs to be said about this syndrome: it is a failure in humanization, which means a failure to confidently deny man’s real situation on this planet.
